Urban Greenspaces: Exploratory Analysis (EDA)

mm5951

2022-12-01

The primary goal of this exploratory data analysis (EDA) is to provide a primary dataset of NYC Urban Greenspaces upon which regression analysis can be conducted with potentially associated dimensions (temperature, econometrics, and health outcomes).

Secondly, this EDA aims to provide:

  • a descriptive analysis of the NYC Urban Greenspaces primary dataset, as well as stratified analysis at the City Council District and Borough levels;
  • relevant data visualizations of the above (notably including a map using the leaflet package and overtime trends);
  • TBD a test of homogeneity to assess the distribution of Urban Greenspaces (UG) at the City Council District and/or Borough levels.

Potential variable keys (that is, to link among datasets) include borough, district (“zonedist1”), NYC building identifiers (“bin” & “bbl”) and coordenades (longitude and latitude).

Data load & wrangling

The primary Urban Greenspaces (UG) dataset is loaded (“UG_df_raw”). Next, str() and skmir::skim() functions are used to delve into the contents and structure of the resulting dataframe.

Next, the “UG_df_raw” is wrangled in order to generate a “UG_df” dataframe to be used for analysis & association to other workstreams of the project:

  • select relevant variables using select()
  • rename certain variables for comprehension using remame()
  • re-order the variables using arrange()
  • drop entries with now total green area available using drop_na()
  • calculate percentage of green coverage of each building, as well as recode() borough names, with mutate()
UG_df = UG_df_raw %>% 
  janitor::clean_names() %>% 
  select(fid:notes, address:ycoord, -doitt_id, -qa, -feat_code, -spdist1, -bbl_fixed) %>% 
  rename(
    UG_id = fid,
    latitude = ycoord,
    longitude = xcoord,
    cons_year = cnstrct_yr,
    green_area = gr_area,
    building_area = bldg_area
  ) %>% 
  mutate(
    prop_gr = prop_gr*100,
    borough = recode(borough,
         BK = "Brooklyn",
         BX = "Bronx",
         MN = "Manhattan", 
         QN = "Queens",
         SI = "Staten Island")
  ) %>% 
  select(UG_id, cons_year, borough, zonedist1, address, ownertype, longitude, latitude, green_area:groundelev, everything()) %>% 
  drop_na(green_area)

NOTE consider removing “bin” and “bbl” if they are not needed to match with tax-related data.

Descriptive analysis

Overall UG_df Datset Analysis

Overall, the “UG_df” contains contains 16 variables related to 736 urban greenspaces in NYC. Details on the nature of its variables and summary values are found in the outputs above (chunk 1 of the data load & wrangling).

The total UG area in NYC sums to 2.6501578^{6} square feet. The following table summarizes the average urban greenspace in NYC, including its size (in square feet), height (in feet) and percentage of green coverage (that is, the proportion of green space within the total building area). Key variables are summarized in the table below using knitr:kable().

UG_df %>% 
  summarize(
    mean_green = mean(green_area, na.rm = TRUE),
    median_green = median(green_area),
    mean_height = mean(heightroof, na.rm = TRUE),
    perc_green = mean(prop_gr, na.rm = TRUE)
    ) %>% 
    knitr::kable(digits = 2)
mean_green median_green mean_height perc_green
3600.76 1173.91 142.63 19.63

Stratified Analysis by Borough

When stratified by borough, differences in the amount of UGs as well as other the indicators used above become apparent. See the table below with a summary.

UG_df %>% 
  group_by(borough) %>% 
  summarize(
    n = n(),
    tot_green = sum(green_area),
    mean_green = mean(green_area, na.rm = TRUE),
    median_green = median(green_area),
    mean_height = mean(heightroof, na.rm = TRUE),
    perc_green = mean(prop_gr, na.rm = TRUE)
    ) %>% 
  arrange(desc(n)) %>% 
  knitr::kable(digits = 2)

Data visualization

Mapping UGs in NYC

Using the leaflet package to plot observations on a NY map. A pal() function is generated to establish a color according to the size of the UG.

pal <- colorNumeric(
  palette = "viridis",
  domain = UG_df$green_area)

UG_map = UG_df %>% 
  mutate(
    green_area = round(green_area, digit = 2),
    heightroof = round(heightroof, digit = 2),
    click_label = 
      str_c("<b>Area ", green_area, " sqft</b><br>Height ", heightroof, " ft<br>")) %>% 
  leaflet() %>% 
  addProviderTiles(providers$CartoDB.Positron) %>% 
  addCircleMarkers(~longitude, ~latitude, radius = .1, color = ~pal(green_area), popup = ~click_label)

UG_map

Interpretation: concentration of UGs in Manhattan, and the southern the bigger.

UGs development overtime in NYC

Next, the construction of UG trends are investigated overtime. To do so, the cumsum() function is used over a generated dummy variable that allocates the value “1” to all UGs. Note that the observations with an invalid or missing construction year are ommited.

UG_overtime = UG_df %>%
  drop_na(cons_year) %>% 
  filter(cons_year !=0) %>% 
  arrange(cons_year) %>% 
  mutate(
    cumsum_dummy = 1,
    cumulative_UG = cumsum(cumsum_dummy)
  )
  
UG_overtime %>% 
  group_by(borough) %>% 
  ggplot(aes(cons_year, cumulative_UG, color = borough)) +
  geom_point(alpha = .5) +
  labs(
    title = "Overtime construction of Urban Greenspaces (UG)",
    x = "Time (year)",
    y = "Number of UG")

Interpretation: progressive construction of UG overtime, rampant trend as of early 2000s (potentially linked to urban planning regulations and greater intest in climate change mitigation strategies).

Consider: split into 5 differnt lines per borough, as example here

Distribution of UG surface by borough

Finally, the distribution of UG surface by borough is investigated. The “UG_df” is first plotted on a boxplot to have a better understanding of outliers. Given the presence of considerable outliers, the plotted green area surface is then limited to 67,000 sqft and visualized through a violin plot and a ridge plot.

Pending : decide which to keep.

UG_boxplot = UG_df %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = green_area, y = borough)) + 
  geom_boxplot() +
  labs(
    title = "Distribution of Urban Greenspaces (UG) surface by borough [boxplot]",
    x = "Green Area (sqft)",
    y = "Borough")

UG_boxplot

UG_ridge = UG_df %>% 
  filter(green_area <67000) %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = green_area, y = borough)) + 
  geom_density_ridges(scale = .85) +
  labs(
    title = "Distribution of Urban Greenspaces (UG) surface by borough [ggrides]",
    x = "Green Area (sqft)",
    y = "Borough")

UG_ridge

UG_violin = UG_df %>% 
  filter(green_area <67000) %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = green_area, y = borough)) + 
  geom_violin(aes(fill = borough), color = "blue", alpha = .5) +
  theme(legend.position = "bottom") +
  labs(

    x = "Green Area (sqft)",
    y = "Borough")

UG_violin

Interpretation: overall UG surface median is low (on the (900, 5000) sqft range depending on the borough), but the presence of outliers is notable. Moreover, Staten Island despite only having only n=4 registered UGs, has the hights mean UG surface area at 4836.36 sqft (potentially translating lower population density and lower prices to urban area).
